</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="72453">Females differ from males by the following characters: a) pronotum slightly shorter than wide in males (LP/WP 0.88-0.89), b) pronotum subtruncate, c) elytra longer and wider (LE/WE 1.38-1.43, WE/WP 1.5-1.67, LE/LP 2.4-2.62) than in males and with oblique faint ridge on dorsolateral surface before mid-length, d) presence of tuft of piliform scales on elytral declivity and e) elytral apex with triangular projection. Otherwise mentioned, females similar to males.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="72453" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="72453">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="72453">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cabras &amp; Medina" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Metapocyrtus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Metapocyrtus (Metapocyrtus) flavomaculata" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="72453" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavomaculata" subGenus="Metapocyrtus">Metapocyrtus (Metapocyrtus) flavomaculata</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. differs from all other species of the subgenus for its unique elytral ornamentation consisting of yellow ochre spots. It bears some superficial resemblance to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schultze" authorityYear="1925" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Metapocyrtus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Metapocyrtus (Metapocyrtus) worcesteri" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="72453" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="worcesteri" subGenus="Metapocyrtus">Metapocyrtus (Metapocyrtus) worcesteri</taxonomicName>
Schultze, 1925 from Zamboanga Province, but can be easily distinguished by the shape of the rostrum and pronotum, the presence of four spots in the pronotum (two at basal parts and two along apical margin), compared to the two spots at mid-length of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="M." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="M. (M.) worcesteri." order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="72453" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="worcesteri." subGenus="M.">M. (M.) worcesteri.</taxonomicName>
The presence of an oblique ridge on the dorsolateral surface before mid-length in the elytra of females of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cabras &amp; Medina" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Metapocyrtus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Metapocyrtus (Metapocyrtus) flavomaculata" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="72453" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavomaculata" subGenus="Metapocyrtus">Metapocyrtus (Metapocyrtus) flavomaculata</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. also distinguishes it.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="72453" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="72453">Etymology</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="72453">Etymology. Latin, flavus = yellow; maculata = spotted. The Latin name refers to the yellow spots on the elytra.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="72453" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="72453">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="72453">The new species is known, so far, in Davao City and Bukidnon.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
